<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-585-265  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 585 265.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 5 1990 v24 n44 p95(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>First the goal, then the gear. (benefits of document imagingsystems) (Image Processing Systems Special Report)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Buren, Gregory.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Key applications for electronic document imaging systems includestorage and retrieval of documents formerly processed in paper ormicrofilm form.andP;  Configurations for this application vary in costand complexity from microcomputer-based systems tomainframe-centered systems capable of handling millions of images.andO;Speed is a crucial consideration when choosing among imagingsystems, as is degree of flexibility afforded by the storage andretrieval mechanisms.andP;  Work-flow automation, another application,can increase a company's control of work processes and eliminatesome stages of processing.andP;  Full-text retrieval helps the imagingsystem user locate documents by knowing a word within the documentinstead of having to rely on knowledge of key words in an index.andO;Imaging systems may also include office automation applicationsthat relate imaging to other corporate information processingactivities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Imaging TechnologyImage processingDocument ProcessingApplicationsInformation Storage and RetrievalOffice Automation.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Imaging systems integrators. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>